    "cheatsheetContent": "You are detecting whether Equation 1 really implies Equation 2 or only almost does.\nEquation 1:\n{{ equation1 }}\nEquation 2:\n{{ equation2 }}\n\nMethod:\n- Compare the two equations carefully and identify whether Equation 2 asks for one extra condition or stronger identity than Equation 1 supplies.\n- If it is a near miss rather than a real implication, answer `FALSE` and give a witness isolating the missing part.\n- If the implication truly holds, answer `TRUE` and give a concise proof.\n- Do not promote a near miss to `TRUE`.\n\nRequired output:\nVERDICT: TRUE or FALSE\nREASONING: name the decisive extra condition or the decisive derivation\nPROOF:\nfill only when VERDICT is TRUE\nCOUNTEREXAMPLE:\nfill only when VERDICT is FALSE\n\nRules:\n- Plain text only.\n- `VERDICT:` must be exactly `TRUE` or `FALSE`.\n- `REASONING:` must not be empty.\n- If `VERDICT: TRUE`, `PROOF:` must be non-empty and `COUNTEREXAMPLE:` empty.\n- If `VERDICT: FALSE`, `COUNTEREXAMPLE:` must be non-empty and `PROOF:` empty.",
